reporting: Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ)
description: Das marokkanische Entwicklungsmodell gerät hinsichtlich einer Sicherstellung von Wirtschaftswachstum, Fortschritt und Entwicklung für alle Regionen Marokkos zunehmend an seine Grenzen. Eine verstärkte Aktivierung und Dynamisierung des Privatsektors kann die Schaffung verbesserter Einkommens- und Beschäftigungsperspektiven für alle Bevölkerungsgruppen Marokkos befördern. Unzureichende Rahmenbedingungen und mangelnder Zugang zu Finanzdienstleistungen führen jedoch dazu, dass der Privatsektor sein Potential derzeit nicht vollständig entfalten kann. ŒHier setzt das FZ-Modul an, indem es Reformen in den Bereichen finanzielle Inklusion, Kapitalmarktentwicklung und Finanzsystemstabilität entlang der Prioritäten der marokkanischen Regierung fördert. Die Umsetzung der Reformen wird mithilfe eines Darlehens in Höhe von insgesamt bis zu 450 Mio. EUR (Reformfinanzierung) an den marokkanischen Staat und in Form einer Begleitmaßnahme in Höhe von 15 Mio. EUR (Transformationsunterstützung) unterstützt. Die Reformen in den drei genannten Bereichen sind in Zusammenarbeit mit dem marokkanischen Finanzministerium und anderen wichtigen Akteuren im Sektor (bspw. Zentralbank) in einer Reformmatrix vereinbart worden, welche auf drei Jahre angelegt ist (2020-2022). Pro Jahr möchte und muss der marokkanische Staat bestimmte Reformschritte gehen. Diese werden in Form von Meilensteinen in der Matrix klar definiert. Die Auszahlung des Darlehens erfolgt ergebnisbasiert: Nur wenn die für ein Jahr vereinbarten Reformschritte (Meilensteine) umgesetzt sind, wird pro Jahr eine Tranche der Reformfinanzierung in den marokkanischen Staatshaushalt ausgezahlt. Insgesamt umfasst die Matrix 17 ambitionierte Reformmaßnahmen, von denen zehn Reformmaßnahmen als auszahlungsrelevant vereinbart worden sind. ŒZiel des FZ-Moduls ist es, die marokkanische Reformagenda umzusetzen. Diese verfolgt ein sozial inklusives Entwicklungsmodell durch strukturell verbesserte Rahmenbedingungen für Investitionen und einen verbesserten Zugang zu Finanzdienstleistungen für Privatpersonen sowie in- und ausländische Privatunternehmen. Zielgruppe im weiteren Sinne ist die gesamte marokkanische Bevölkerung, die nach der Umsetzung politischer Reformen von verbesserten ökonomischen Rahmenbedingungen durch nachhaltiges Wirtschafts- und Beschäftigungswachstum profitiert. Unmittelbare Zielgruppe des Vorhabens sind vulnerable Bevölkerungsgruppen sowie in- und ausländische Privatunternehmen, insbesondere KKMU und Startups, und deren Angestellte. ŒDas FZ-Modul ist Teil der aus der G20-Initiative "Compact with Africa" (CwA) hervorgegangenen Reformpartnerschaft zwischen der deutschen und der marokkanischen Regierung.

reporting: Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ)
description: Das Vorhaben "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für KMU" dient der Verbesserung und Sicherstellung des Zugangs zu Krediten für marokkanische kleine und mittlere Unternehmen (KMU). Zugang zu bedarfsgerechten Finanzdienstleitungen für KMU ist für die Eindämmung der negativen Auswirkungen der COVID-19-Pandemie auf die marokkanische Wirtschaft von großer Bedeutung. Œ ŒDazu wird im Rahmen der FZ-Module "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für KMU" ein zinsverbilligtes Darlehen in Höhe von (i.H.v.) bis zu 50 Mio. EUR gewährt, sowie ein Zuschusses i.H.v. 4 Mio. EUR im Rahmen einer Begleitmaßnahme. Die Finanzierung des FZ-Moduls "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für Kleinstunternehmen" erfolgt mittels eines Zuschusses i.H.v. 20 Mio. EUR. Diese beiden FZ-Module sind ein integraler Bestandteil des deutschen Beitrags zur Abfederung der wirtschaftlichen Auswirkungen infolge der COVID-19-Pandemie. Sie ergänzen das zinsverbilligte Darlehen "Corona-Soforthilfe in Marokko - Garantiemechanismus zur Abfederung wirtschaftlicher Auswirkungen" sowie den Zuschuss "Corona-Soforthilfe in Marokko - Garantiemechanismus zur Abfederung wirtschaftlicher Auswirkungen für kleinste und junge Unternehmen". Œ ŒZiel der FZ-Maßnahmen ist es, den Zugang zu Finanzierung für KMU sicherzustellen bzw. zu verbessern und somit das Überleben von KMU sowie die Wiederbelebung ihrer Wirtschaftstätigkeit zu fördern. Die Zielgruppe sind marokkanische Unternehmen, insbesondere formelle und informelle kleine und mittlere Unternehmen.

reporting: Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ)
description: Das Vorhaben "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für Kleinstunternehmen" dient der Verbesserung und Sicherstellung des Zugangs zu Krediten für marokkanische Kleinstunternehmen. Zugang zu bedarfsgerechten Finanzdienstleitungen für KKMU, insbesondere für Kleinstunternehmen, ist für die Eindämmung der negativen Auswirkungen der COVID-19-Pandemie auf die marokkanische Wirtschaft von großer Bedeutung. Œ ŒDazu erfolgt die Finanzierung des FZ-Moduls "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für Kleinstunternehmen" mittels eines Zuschusses in Höhe von (i.H.v.) 20 Mio. EUR. Im Rahmen des FZ-Moduls "Kreditgarantiemechanismus für KMU" wird ein zinsverbilligtes Darlehen i.H.v. bis zu 50 Mio. EUR gewährt, sowie ein Zuschusses i.H.v. 4 Mio. EUR im Rahmen einer Begleitmaßnahme. Diese beiden FZ-Module sind ein integraler Bestandteil des deutschen Beitrags zur Abfederung der wirtschaftlichen Auswirkungen infolge der COVID-19-Pandemie. Sie ergänzen das zinsverbilligte Darlehen "Corona-Soforthilfe in Marokko - Garantiemechanismus zur Abfederung wirtschaftlicher Auswirkungen" sowie den Zuschuss "Corona-Soforthilfe in Marokko - Garantiemechanismus zur Abfederung wirtschaftlicher Auswirkungen für kleinste und junge Unternehmen". Œ ŒZiel der FZ-Maßnahmen ist es, den Zugang zu Finanzierung für marokkanische Kleinstunternehmen sicherzustellen bzw. zu verbessern und somit ihr Überleben sowie die Wiederbelebung ihrer Wirtschaftstätigkeit zu fördern.

reporting: Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ)
description: Das Vorhaben unterstützt die marokkanische Regierung bei der Förderung klimafreundlicher urbaner Mobilität. Im Rahmen eines Modellvorhabens in Essaouira soll der öffentliche Nahverkehr durch ein verbessertes Angebot an miteinander verknüpften Transportdienstleistungen und -wegen gestärkt werden. Die Finanzierung erfolgt über den marokkanischen Fonds d'Accompagnement des Réformes du Transport ("FART"). Œ ŒDas Vorhaben unterstützt Marokko bei einer effizienteren Nutzung von Energieressourcen und trägt damit zur Reduzierung von CO2-Emissionen und zum globalen Klimaschutz bei. Es knüpft damit an die Ziele und Indikatoren des Programms "Energie" der deutsch-marokkanischen Zusammenarbeit an. Darüber hinaus trägt das Vorhaben zu einer Verbesserung des Zugangs der Einwohner zu Arbeitsstätten und sozialen Dienstleistungen bei (insbesondere Bildungseinrichtungen, Krankenhaus, städtische und Provinzverwaltung, etc.).

reporting: European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
description: EBRD has provided a sovereign guaranteed loan of EUR 200 million to the Societe  Nador West Med (NWM) for infrastructure development at the new Nador West Med  Port in Morocco (the 'Project'). The loan will be used for the construction of  the port infrastructure (breakwaters, quays, dredging, etc) which will be used  by private concessionaires for commercial handling activities.  The Government of Morocco (GoM) is developing a major new port and industrial  complex around 30km from the town of Nador, on Morocco's Mediterranean coast.

reporting: European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
description: The EBRD is providing a loan to the Office National de l'Electricite et de  l'Eau Potable ('ONEE' or the 'Company') of Morocco. The sovereign-guaranteed  senior loan of up to EUR 41.2 million will finance the rehabilitation of 11  hydropower plants and 3 dams in Morocco (the 'Project'). The Project will also  include the establishment of a Project Preparation and Implementation Unit  ('PPIU') to prepare the detailed design for the works, prepare the complete  tender documents, assist with the procurement process, build ONEE's  environmental and social monitoring capabilities, and ensure the successful  implementation of the Project.

reporting: European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
description: Provision of a sovereign loan of up to EUR 150 million in favour of the Kingdom  of Morocco (the "Country") to co-finance: (i) the construction of key  components of the Saiss water transfer network comprised of the main  distribution pipeline as well as the primary and secondary distribution  networks (the "Saiss II" component); and (ii) the rehabilitation and  modernisation of the water distribution network and full conversion to drip-fed  watering system in the Garet perimeter (the "Garet" component), (altogether,  the "Project").  The Saiss II component is part of a staged programme to preserve the Saiss  aquifer and promote sustainable water management within the Saiss plain. As  part of this programme, the Bank has approved a sovereign loan of up to EUR 120  million and mobilized grant financing of EUR 30 million from the Green Climate  Fund (the "GCF") to finance the construction of a 135 km (a 45 km section of  the main transfer pipeline with a total length of 62 km outside the Saiss plain  and a 90 km main distribution pipeline within the Saiss plain) water transfer  pipeline from the M'Dez dam to the boundary of the Saiss perimeter (Saiss water  conservation project  or the "Saiss I").

reporting: VVSG - Association of Flemish Cities and Municipalities
description: Ce programme VVSG vise à renforcer la capacité de la commune rurale d’Ouled Daoud Zekhanine et la société civile à élaborer une politique de l’économie sociale et solidaire (y compris l’établissement et la gestion d’un marché local), à pérenniser le développement économique social et solidaire (consolidation, augmentation et diversification des activités génératrices de revenue (AGR), y compris un volet d’écotourisme, l’accès renforcé au marché et la promotion des produits de terroirs) et améliorer la participation de la population locale dans cette politique. Cela couvre la création de structures spécifiques (par ex. une association de coordination et de concertation pour le développement rural et local) et la réalisation d’actions et d’outils de travail, des éléments cruciaux pour l’avenir socioéconomique de la population d’Ouled Daoud Zekhanine et un développement local durable. Ainsi le programme VVSG contribue à établir une bonne gouvernance locale au Maroc via un partenariat multi-acteurs entre une ville flamande (Anvers), une commune marocaine (Ouled Daoud Zekhanine), des associations de la diaspora marocaine à Anvers et leurs partenaires actifs dans la commune marocaine.

reporting: Association pour la Promotion de l'Education et de la Formation à l'Etranger
description: Depuis 2013, l’APEFE promeut l’entrepreunariat féminin dans plusieurs régions du Maroc. Le programme « Min Ajliki » qui s’inscrit dans ce cadre est un succès et a permis de former 500 cadres à l’accompagnement des porteuses de projet, de sensibiliser 60.000 femmes parmi lesquelles 700 formées à l’entrepreneuriat et 1200 accompagnées en pré-création d’entreprises. Pour la période 2017-2021, l’APEFE a la volonté d’étendre le programme à tout le territoire marocain. Malgré la volonté affichée et l’évolution de la législation, le Maroc doit faire face à de nombreux défis tels notamment, la prévalence du secteur informel dans l’économie, facteur de précarisation des travailleurs et le taux de chômage élevé de la population en général et des jeunes, diplômés ou non, et des femmes en particulier. L’objectif du programme est de soutenir le développement d’un emploi et d’un entrepreunariat justes, équitables et inclusifs pour les femmes. Cette cible répond par ailleurs à une volonté globale de parvenir à l’égalité entre les sexes et d’autonomiser toutes les femmes et les filles. Min Ajliki 2.0 aura recourt à divers supports numériques (E-learning, E-commerce et d’E-intermédiation, E-mailing et newsletters, médias sociaux, application mobile, « SMS-ing », centre d’appels, mass media, etc.) et s’aligne sur le renforcement de la digitalisation intégrée au sein des huit institutions partenaires.

Morocco II - EDUCATION AND TRAINING FOR EMPLOYABILITY PROJECT - Secondary Education Activity: The Activity aims to improve the quality of secondary education by piloting a participatory approach to school improvement in 90 schools across three regions of Morocco. The activity is investing in reforms to school governance, coupled with targeted investments in infrastructure, technology, and training for teachers and school administrators. The activity is also investing in improvements to the education management information system.

Morocco II - Land Productivity Project - Rural Land Activity: the activity is developing a faster and more inclusive process for granting titles on irrigated collective lands to individual men and women smallholder farmers and their families who currently farm the land.

Morocco II - Land Productivity Project - Industrial Land Activity: the activity is piloting a market-driven public-private partnership (PPP) approach to industrial zone development and management to foster sustainability and private sector investment.

Morocco II - Land Productivity Project - Governance Activity: the activity is improving land governance and addressing land market constraints to investment and productivity, in part through the development of a National Land Strategy and action plan, and by supporting priority measures to address those constraints, including those focused on strengthening women's land rights.

Through a competitive process approved by MCC, the Government has appointed a fiscal agent (the "Fiscal Agent") to provide fiscal agent services to MCA-Morocco II. The Fiscal Agent will provide a broad range of financial management services required by MCA-Morocco II to implement the Program, including funds control, disbursement documentation and management, cash management and accounting. Through a competitive process approved by MCC, the Government has appointed a procurement agent (the "Procurement Agent") to provide procurement agent services to MCA-Morocco II. The Procurement Agent will administer all Program and administrative procurements, and provide specified procurement appropriate activities required by MCA-Morocco II to implement the Program.

Brulocalis collabore avec l'UVCW dans la mise en œuvre du Programme MAROC.

Disenfranchised individuals and groups will increasingly change their life paths to advance economically and socially, and increasingly evolve in environments that foster ownership of the community by its inhabitants

Rohill develops, produces and maintains mission-critical mobile communications solutions. Rohill has developed a new product/concept called SUMMUM S-MVNE (Secure, Uniform, Mission-Critical, Modifiable, Unified and Mobile - Mobile Virtual Network Enabler). SUMMUM S-MVNE provides an open communication platform, which is tailored for the mission and business critical market. This solution makes it possible to combine both a narrowband TETRA network with a broadband network and its possibilities. In this demonstration project Rohill will, together with Autoroutes du Maroc (ADM) (owns a TETRA network) and Orange (public broadband provider), demonstrate the enormous potential of such an innovative solution.

The overall objective of this project is to contribute to the empowerment of female Moroccan migrant workers participating in the Spain-Morocco circular migration programme in their home communities. More specifically, this project aims to ensure that the Government of Morocco implements a socio-economic empowerment programme for female migrant workers that responds to their profiles and needs. At the end of the project, the Moroccan Government through its institutions, including ANAPEC (Agence Nationale de Promotion de l’Emploi et des Compétences), will have a better understanding of the needs of female circular migrant workers throughout the circular migration process and will have developed and targeted its capacities to support these women in their empowerment trajectory through a range of services throughout the migration cycle and more specifically during the post-return phase.

The project will help Moroccan authorities reinforce the production, the analysis and the diffusion mechanisms of migration data both at a national and African level. In line with the 2030 Agenda for sustainable development, the project meets the challenges Morocco is facing in terms of migration and its place at the regional level. Moreover, it will contribute to promote gender equality through the reinforcement of gender-disaggregated data collection, analysis and use enabling the development and the implementation of gender-sensitive policies.
The overall objective of the project is to strengthen the capabilities of the Moroccan Regulatory Body in the field of nuclear and radiation safety as well as radioactive waste management.
MO3.0/15  ''Support to the Regulatory Body of Morocco for capacity building and for enhancing the regulatory framework for nuclear and radiation safety'' -

This project seeks to contribute to address issues related to development and climate change, that might be faced also but other countries with a similar profile. The project foresees a threefold initiative based on the following axes: (1) Analysis of migration paths and profiles of Moroccan returnees involved in agro-ecology projects in order to better understand the reasons and the factors that have motivated them to undertake these kinds of initiatives; (2) Economic and agronomic analysis of the projects will be carried on in order to demonstrate their economic potential as well as the social impact of these activities on their environment (clients, employees and neighbours); (3) Development of targeted pedagogical and technical tools and the organization of a final conference in order to share good practices and decision makers, diaspora associations and other stakeholders.

The aim of the project is to improve assistance and protection of unaccompanied and separated children in Morocco. The intervention foresees to work on both immediate needs and long-term results. On the one hand, it will provide emergency protection measures through a short term action, on the other hand it will work on long run results such as the development of the child protection tools and coordinated strategies among key national and international actors.
The main goal of this cooperation project is to improve the quality of the phytosanitary control system in Morocco and to improve trade conditions in phyto-material between the two countries.

Building on 15 years of experience in Morocco, this project aims to contribute to improving the migration management system through migrants' protection. It will reach this objective by offering the alternative of assisted voluntary return and reintegration to a maximum number of 400 migrants in vulnerable situations in Morocco. The different components of this project will have a specific focus on migrants in vulnerable situation especially unaccompanied migrant children, aged-out beneficiaries, migrants with health needs, potential victims of trafficking and those exposed to gender-related vulnerabilities.

This project aims to contribute to improving the migration management system through migrants’ protection and assistance. It will reach this objective by offering the alternative of Assisted Voluntary Return and Reintegration (AVRR) to a maximum number of 250 migrants in vulnerable situations in Morocco.

This project will help strengthen the economic reintegration of Moroccans returning from Germany, through the development of self-employment and / or professional integration activities. In a transversal way, this action will also contribute to ensure a sustainable and holistic reintegration approach where the social and psychosocial needs of returning Moroccans will be strengthened and where the coordination, referral and support mechanisms among the main stakeholders in Morocco will be strengthened at the structural level to improve the sustainable reintegration of returning Moroccans.

Incoming poultry mission with Moroccan counterpart, in order to improve the performance of the local egg production sector in a sustainable way. Dutch knowledge and technology is shown and discussions between Moroccan and Dutch parties is facilitated. The visit focuses on the valorisation of the output products that are the eggs on one hand and the by-products on the other hand: waste (manure) and the laying hens at the end of their production cycle.

Morocco faces huge challenges in its important horticulture sector (low-investment in greenhouses, unskilled labour, poor reliability and quality of produce, increasing scarcity and price of inputs (water, fertilizers, electricity). Morocco and The Netherlands decided to join forces on making Morocco’s horticulture more sustainable and to do through setting up a Centre d’ Excellence Horticole. The main goal is to strengthen the relationship between Morocco and the Netherlands in the field of research and higher education, as well as to strengthen Moroccan capacity in covered horticulture techniques and technology while in the meantime creating business opportunities for Dutch companies in horticulture technology.The Centre of Excellence for Horticulture will act as main research and education arena and will house research and educational facilities for research and education staff of the Centre, PHD Students doing research, students following education and performing BSC and MSC level research all in sustainable horticulture as well research assistants, greenhouse workers and the Centre’s administrative and finance support staff. The Centre of Excellence will have a strong outreach to the private sector. Through demonstrations of new techniques and technology to the private sector (farm managers and workforce) innovation and new knowledge in horticulture will be disseminated and introduced at the level of local growers. Furthermore, the private Moroccan sector will take place in the board of the Centre of Excellence and will have a voice in setting the research project agenda. On the longer term, there is a link with the private sector through students who are acquainted with the latest techniques and technology in horticulture. Through its direct links with the private (production) sector, CEH will add to the improvement of productivity and product quality and will stimulate sustainable production methods in Moroccan greenhouses in order to lessen the pressure on the environment and to meet the needs and requirements of the EU-market. By testing and demonstrating new technologies and transferring the results to different stakeholders, the centre can help the Moroccan growers to strengthen their competitiveness. A centre of excellence for horticulture would furthermore prove to the policy makers the added value of investing in certain new and sustainable technologies in the horticulture sector and the necessity to stimulate investment in such a transition through government funds. After two years, this will have led to the following results:•\tA greenhouse which has been built in accordance with the jointly developed scientific program for the Centre of Excellence.•\tA joint Moroccan Dutch 2 year research programme in which CEH is instrumental.•\t5 joint research projects of which the results have been actively disseminated within the Dutch and Moroccan horticulture sector.•\tAppr 50 Moroccan students and PhD students will have been educated and done research in the greenhouse through the CEH •\tMoroccan researchers will have access to CEH and its facilities.•\tAppr 500 Moroccan farmers and professionals in horticulture will have attended to trainings and demonstrations at the CEH, in which the greenhouse will be instrumental.•\tApproximately 40 business leads for Dutch companies.

The Orange Corners Innovation Fund (OCIF) provides young entrepreneurs in the Orange Corners programme with access to funding of up to €50.000. This allows the entrepreneurs to develop their idea in a product/proposition that can enter the market.As OCIF aims to stimulate innovation, the innovative-aspect of the business will be an important criteria for the selection of participants in the programme. It will be a condition that each business idea will have positive social- or ecological impact and addresses at least one SDG. Furthermore, each entrepreneur will have to commit him/herself fully for the period of the incubation programme. If a business idea fits within the circular economy this will be a big plus.

Orange Corners Innovation Fund enables Orange Corners incubatees to get access to capital (up to €30.000) and develop their idea in a product/proposition that can enter the market. As OCIF aims to stimulate innovation, the innovative-aspect of the business will be an important criteria for the selection of participants in the programme. It will be a condition that each business idea will have positive social- or ecological impact and addresses at least one SDG. Furthermore, each incubatee will have to commit him/herself fully for the period of the incubation programme. If a business idea fits within the circular economy this will be a big plus

This funding concerns an FAO project with co funders Norway (60%) and the Netherlands (40%). The project, lasting four years (2020-2024) aims to promote the sustainable development of the aquaculture sector in Morocco:  foster food security and nutrition for Moroccans and create of decent jobs in this sector. This will be done through an intensive training programme involving technicians, farmers, teachers and students and setting up and equipment of  a training and education station on aquaculture.

This projects focuses on:•\treduction of water consumption in industrial processes, as reduction if relevant is always more feasible than reuse;•\tlocal reuse of treated and upgraded industrial wastewater for internal reuse, reuse at other industrial facilities, watering parks and possible local agriculturein Tangier, Morocco.The project will provide insights in the context and potential of Tangier’s urban and industrial water and providing circular economy solutions in the segment of urban and industrial water and wastewater. The project covers the inventory of local options for reduction of industrial water consumption and reuse of wastewater as a renewable source for different classes of water, that are socially acceptable, economically viable, environmentally sound and technically feasible. In the long term, the project will contribute to promoting circular economy solutions in the segment of water, including wastewater related energy recovery and recovery of reusable raw materials to relevant stakeholders.

During this Capacity Building project foreseen in early 2021, 9 selected Track II OCIF startups will receive business mentoring and strategic advice. Furthermore will be connected to business angel networks and potential follow-up investment opportunities.

With this project, La Caravane Orange Corners incubation program in Morocco will be developed. This will strengthen the start-up infrastructure in Morocco by offering an incubation program in different regions in Morocco for 60 young social entrepreneurs in total over 2 years and enabling them to create new innovative businesses and social enterprises. At least 50% of these social entrepreneurs will be women, thereby supporting equal opportunities for women.The incubates get the opportunity to collaborate and work with like-minded individuals in order to start and grow their business. The incubation program, focusing particularly on entrepreneurs in 4 different regions (among which Casablanca); offers training, business development support, masterclasses, events, coaching and mentoring sessions. Through collaboration between the private and public sector, Orange Corners combines forces to contribute towards the economic growth of Morocco and strengthen the Moroccan start-up ecosystem.

With this project, Sportive Orange Corners Maroc incubation program will be developed. This will strengthen the sport start-up infrastructure in Morocco by offering an incubation program for 40 young social entrepreneurs in the sport sector. Sportive Orange Corners Maroc is enabling them to create new innovative businesses and social enterprises. At least 50% of these social entrepreneurs will be women, thereby supporting equal opportunities for women.The incubatees get the opportunity to collaborate and work with like-minded individuals in order to start and grow their sport related business. The incubation program, focusing particularly on entrepreneurs in Casablanca and Rabat; offers training, business development support, masterclasses, events, coaching and mentoring sessions. Through collaboration between the private and public sector, Orange Corners combines forces to contribute towards the economic growth of Morocco and strengthen the Moroccan start-up ecosystem

This two day digital incoming visitors programme on Circular Economy showcases Dutch best practices on three CE themes (plastics, e-waste, circular agriculture) to influentials from 7 African countries: Côte d’Ivoire, Ghana, Kenya, Morocco, Nigeria, Senegal, and South-Africa. The goal of the programme is to stimulate circular business models in plastics, electronics and agriculture by removing obstacles in legislation and regulations, technology and knowledge through knowledge transfer and matchmaking with Dutch companies and organizations.

This project enables RVO to design and implement more gender-sensitive PSD interventions. Having a gender specialist with a PSD background “on call” the PSD Toolkit interventions will provide insight into the opportunities PSD Coaches have to make their project more gender inclusive (becoming alert of our own blind spots).

A study visit by Dutch saline agriculture experts to Morocco will result in a tangible and relevant proposal for a cooperation program and/or pilot project on saline farming in one or two specific regions, meeting the needs and demands of relevant Moroccan stakeholders, and contributing to climate adaptation and mitigation in agriculture.
